  "prompt": "What is education like in South Africa?",
  "response": "Education in South Africa has undergone significant changes since the end of apartheid in 1994. Here are some key characteristics:\n\n1. Structure\n- 12 years of schooling (6 years primary, 6 years secondary)\n- Compulsory education from ages 7-15\n- National curriculum called the Curriculum and Assessment Policy Statement (CAPS)\n\n2. Language\n- 11 official languages\n- English is often used as the primary language of instruction\n- Students can often learn in their native language during early years\n\n3. Challenges\n- Significant inequality between wealthy and poor schools\n- Infrastructure problems in many rural and township schools\n- Shortages of qualified teachers\n- High dropout rates\n- Limited resources in disadvantaged areas\n\n4. Higher Education\n- Many universities and technical colleges\n- Some world-renowned institutions like University of Cape Town and University of Pretoria\n- Increasing focus on making higher education more accessible\n\n5. Public vs Private Schools\n- Public schools serve the majority of students\n- Private schools offer higher quality education but are expensive\n- Significant disparities in educational quality between these sectors\n\n6. Post-Apartheid Reforms\n- Efforts to create a more equitable education system\n- Increased access for previously marginalized populations\n- Ongoing work to improve overall educational quality",
